{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1edbea17-aae3-47ad-81de-38e7895251d2","content":"To switch to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), you need to make these changes:\n\n**1. Register your package on NuGet.org for trusted publishing:**\n- Go to NuGet.org → your package → Manage → Publishing → add a trusted publisher\n- Configure your GitHub repository, workflow file path, and optionally the environment\n\n**2. Update your workflow:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write  # Required for OIDC token request\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n\n      # ... build/pack steps ...\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n- Add `permissions: id-token: write`\n- Remove `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` from `dotnet nuget push`\n- No API key is needed — the OIDC token is automatically exchanged\n- Optionally use a GitHub environment for additional protection (approval gates, branch restrictions)\n\n**3. Clean up:**\n- Remove the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo settings once confirmed working\n\nThe `dotnet` CLI (6.0.400+) automatically detects the OIDC context and authenticates without an explicit key.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"86f7e695-21d5-4531-9e02-f984bb5b297b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key secret to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet - I don't need to search their repository since they're asking for guidance on how to make this change.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about what's needed to switch to NuGet trusted publishing with OIDC.","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"FE12:374A11:1333CBA:158A498:6A066EDE"},"id":"50bd6b33-f629-46f0-84c7-b6ee39157655","timestamp":"2026-05-15